1. Scenario types to implement (limit to 5) 
If you only build five scenarios, consider focusing on what consumes time and attention in a real SOC, not edge-case nation-state activity. 
Recommended scenarios 

1.	Phishing → Credential Compromise → Lateral Movement 
o	Initial user reported phishing email 
o	Successful credential capture 
o	Suspicious signin or mailbox access 
o	Secondary activity (mailbox rules, MFA fatigue attempt, or internal phishing) 
o	Why: This is one of the most common real-world incident chains we see 

2.	Endpoint Malware / Suspicious Process Execution 
o	Defender/XDR alert on a workstation 
o	Ambiguous signal (living off the land tools, PowerShell, scheduled task) 
o	Requires triage, scoping, and containment—not just “delete the file” 
o	Why: Most alerts are not clean malware hits; judgment matters 

3.	Misconfiguration Leading to Exposure 
o	Example: logging disabled on a critical server, overly permissive firewall rule, or stale service account 
o	Students must discover the gap before or after suspicious activity 
o	Why: Real incidents often start with control failure, not attacker brilliance 

4.	Web Application or Perimeter Alert with Low Context 
o	WAF / firewall alert with IP reputation data 
o	Conflicting signals (some tools say “high risk,” others don’t) 
o	Students must decide: block, monitor, or escalate 
o	Why: This mirrors daily triage work and threat intel correlation 

5.	User Reported “Something Feels Off” 
o	Vague ticket or email from a user 
o	No clean alerts at first 
o	Students must gather logs, ask clarifying questions, and decide severity 
o	Why: Many real investigations start this way, not from perfect alerts 

2. Common blind spots to intentionally avoid 
Based on real environments: 
•	Perfect visibility: Don’t give students complete logs by default. Missing or delayed telemetry is realistic.  
•	Single tool answers: No one tool tells the full story. Require correlation across sources (endpoint + email + identity). 
•	Binary “malicious vs benign” outcomes: Most investigations end as “suspicious but unconfirmed.” That’s normal. 
•	Ignoring documentation: Force students to document decisions even when the answer is “no action taken”.  

3. Operational challenges worth simulating 
These are realistic and valuable for students to experience: 
•	Time pressure 
o	Multiple alerts arriving at once 
o	Interruptions mid-investigation 
•	Imperfect communication 
o	Vague tickets 
o	Delayed responses from “users” or “IT teams” 
•	Context switching 
o	Students must pause one incident to handle another 
o	Mirrors real SOC workload patterns 

4. External constraints to intentionally model 
To keep the range realistic: 
•	Tool limitations 
o	Rate-limited queries 
o	Delayed log ingestion 
o	Partial data from one system 
•	Staffing constraints 
o	One student handling multiple incidents 
o	No “Tier 3 expert” available on demand 
•	Approval delays 
o	How to deal with speedbumps like approval being required for blocking an IP, disabling an account, or isolating a host. 
o	Reflects real change control processes 

5. Skills students should develop (and how to test them) 
Core skills to build 
•	Triage and prioritization 
•	Evidence preservation 
•	Clear written incident notes 
•	Knowing when not to escalate 
•	Communicating uncertainty professionally 
Practical task ideas 
•	Require a one-page incident summary before containment actions 
•	Force students to choose:  
o	Escalate vs. monitor 
o	Contain vs. observe 
•	Penalize:  
o	Poor documentation 
o	Overreaction without evidence 

6. Real-world KPIs to measure success 
Avoid flashy metrics. Use what SOCs track: 
Operational KPIs 
•	Time to Triage (TTT) – how quickly the alert is understood 
•	Time to Containment (TTC) – if containment is justified 
•	False Positive Rate – did they overreact? 
•	Documentation Quality – could another analyst take over? 
•	Coverage Awareness – did they recognize logging gaps? 
 
Final guidance for the students 
A good cyber range does not reward heroics. It rewards sound judgment, calm triage, clear communication, and knowing your limits. 
